  "body": "**FEATURE REQUEST**:\r\n\r\nAs of today current self hosting model is as follows: \r\n1. Load the Static Pod specification from disk (from /etc/kubernetes/manifests)\r\n2. Extract the PodSpec from that Static Pod specification\r\n3. Mutate the PodSpec to be compatible with self-hosting (add the right labels, taints, etc. so it can schedule correctly)\r\n4. Build a new DaemonSet object for the self-hosted component in question. Use the above mentioned PodSpec\r\n5. Create the DaemonSet resource. Wait until the Pods are running.\r\n6. Remove the Static Pod manifest file. The kubelet will stop the original Static Pod-hosted component that was running.\r\n7. The self-hosted containers should now step up and take over.\r\n...\r\n\r\nA problem arises when we have a power failure condition.  Because we no longer have a manifest of what was running we can no longer restart the control-plane components. \r\n\r\nA very simple workaround would be the following: \r\n1. Add a --checkpoint-path flag with package defaults to /var/lib/kubernetes/checkpoints such that the kubelet can safely write to this location and follow standard conventions. \r\n2. On startup, have the kubelet read in the manifest-path as usual. \r\n3. Also read in the --checkpoint-path if specified\r\n4. Prior to pod startup:\r\n   A. Check the pod for a well defined annotation or label.\r\n   A. delete old checkpoints (if there is one) \r\n   B. write named_YYYYMMDDHHMM manifest to the checkpoint location.\r\n\r\nThis way the kubelet keeps an active record of it's running pods.  There are other complexities around various other checkpointing ideas, and we've (@luxas and myself) decided that this is the bare minimum change that is simple and will enable us to move forwards. \r\n\r\nTODO: We will likely need a minor iteration for configmaps as well. \r\n\r\n/kind feature\r\n/cc @kubernetes/sig-node-feature-requests @kubernetes/sig-cluster-lifecycle-feature-requests \r\n@roberthbailey @dchen1107 @luxas @jbeda \r\n",
